    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "image",
              "identifier": "media-2929789",
              "metadata": {
                "anchor": "2929789",
                "title": "Figure 1",
                "abstract": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Morphing between a sphere geometry and two target geometries "
                  }
                ]
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You control these transitions by associating an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmorpher"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object with a node using its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1408022-morpher"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. The morpher maintains an array of target geometries and a set of weights associated with each. When all weights are zero, the surface takes the form of the base geometry (from the node’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1407966-geometry"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property). When you use the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmorpher/1522886-setweight"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method to increase a weight to "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "1.0"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", the surface takes the form of the geometry at the corresponding index in the morpher’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmorpher/1523572-targets"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " array. If you use a variety of weight values for several targets, the surface takes a form that proportionally interpolates between the target geometries."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can also animate weights implicitly or explicitly using keypath animations. For example, the following code creates a morph animation that transitions one target weight back and forth repeatedly:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "codeListing",
          "code": [
            "CABasicAnimation *animation = [CABasicAnimation animationWithKeyPath:@\"morpher.weights[0]\"];",
            "animation.fromValue = @0.0;",
            "animation.toValue = @1.0;",
            "animation.autoreverses = YES;",
            "animation.repeatCount = INFINITY;",
            "animation.duration = 5;",
            "[node addAnimation:animation forKey:nil];"
          ],
          "syntax": "occ",
          "metadata": {
            "anchor": "2134058",
            "title": "Listing 1"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A morpher and its target geometries may be loaded from a scene file or created programmatically. The base geometry and all target geometries must be topologically identical—that is, they must contain the same number and structural arrangement of vertices."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
